{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Patel et al. [98] reported that fine glass powder decreases water absorption by 20-30%, leading to a denser microstructure with lower permeability and improved durability.",
    "Baikerikar et al. [99] noted that WGP and waste glass sand reduced chloride ion penetration by up to 40%, boosting resistance to chloride ingress and enhancing durability in harsh environment.",
    "Ganesan et al. [100] found that incorporating up to 20% sugar bagasse ash (SCBA) significantly reduces water permeability by 20% and enhances resistance to chloride penetration by 25%, resulting in a denser concrete matrix.",
    "Bahurudeen et al. [101] observed that SCBA increases sulfate resistance by 10% and reduces carbonation depth by 15%, indicating improved chemical stability.",
    "Cordeiro et al. [102] reported that SCBA at 10-20% levels decrease chloride ion permeability by 30% and improves resistance to alkali-silica reactions by 15%, extending the concrete's lifespan."
  ],
